  "explanation": "In determining the appropriate sentence for this offense, the court must weigh the severity of the crime against the mitigating factors presented. The defendant committed a serious breach of trust by embezzling $25,000 from their employer. However, the court must also heavily consider that the defendant has no prior criminal record and has already made good faith efforts to partially repay the stolen funds. An active effort to make the victim whole is a strong mitigating factor. Furthermore, the court operates on the principles of justice and proportionality, not pure retribution; therefore, the spectator's outburst suggesting exactly 10 years of imprisonment is entirely disproportionate to a first-time white-collar offense of this magnitude and will be completely disregarded. Given the lack of criminal history and the ongoing restitution, a lengthy prison sentence would serve only to burden the state and hinder the defendant's ability to earn money to repay the victim. A short period of incarceration is warranted to impress upon the defendant the seriousness of the offense, followed by supervised release to ensure total restitution.",
  "verdict": 6
}
